  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Current treatment protocol for pediatric femoral shaft fractures is immediate spica casting
      for patients 6 years and younger and for patients over 6 years and older is percutaneous or
      open placement of titanium elastic intramedullary nails. The investigators would like to
      evaluate the current treatment protocol by comparing those patients 6 years and younger
      treated with closed reduction and spica casting to those 6 years and younger treated with
      percutaneous pinned with titanium elastic intramedullary nails or submuscular plating. The
      investigators will be comparing their post-operative functional level, pain management,
      impact on family and complications through chart and x-ray reviews. The goal is to improve
      patient care pre and post-operatively for those who have sustained a femoral shaft fracture 6
      years old and younger and increase the knowledge of those residents/physicians who care for
      this patient population.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
